Old Post Office Hotel
Description: Prior to Donald Trump's official bid for the White House, the Trump Organization secured a 60-year lease with the U.S. government to renovate a historic post office in Washington, D.C., into a luxury, mixed-use development. The arrangement presents ongoing concerns now that Donald Trump is the U.S. government's chief executive. His position as both landlord and tenant opens opportunities for self-dealing that could prioritize his business interests over government efficiency. Additionally, foreign dignitaries and business representatives may book hotel stays and events as a means of currying favor with the president. A contractual clause designed to avoid such conflicts of interest prevents any elected official from sharing or benefiting from the lease. Because Trump did not divest of his business interest upon taking office, he may be violating the contract. However, his interests as either landlord and tenant would not be served by terminating the lease.

Name: Trump Victory
InternalNotes:
Hi @Lynn Walsh  I created this record today b/c it showed up in one of the newscomber stories and is likely to come up more and more as the campaign gets underway. Can you please review and, if you think it's good to go, move the draft into the Description field and mark "publishable" as approved? I am setting the conflict status as "active" but LMK if you disagree with that. And one more question: Do you think we should create a conflict record for the RNC and just tag both it and Trump Victory together in any stories related to either? Thank you! 

SOURCES: https://www.politico.com/story/2018/12/18/trump-machine-swallows-rnc-1067875
https://www.cnn.com/2018/12/18/politics/trump-2020-campaign-rnc/index.html
Draft Description: "Trump Victory," Pres. Trump's re-election committee, is in the news for concerns that it accepted contributions from foreign nationals. Only American citizens and green card holders are allowed to contribute to political campaigns. The committee is uniquely tied to the Republican National Committee: Rather than operate independently but in coordination with the RNC's election efforts, as is traditional, the president's campaign and national party share resources for a unified strategy. The formal relationship and deep tie likely would present a challenge to any would-be Republican challenger.

Name: Cindy Yang
InternalNotes: @Lynn Walsh  Here's another new one. I set this conflict status to "unclear" because she's not been charged with wrongdoing — she's just suspected of it. Does that sound right to you?
Draft Description: Cindy Yang is a conservative Chinese-American from Florida who, in 2017, began peddling access to Pres. Trump through a company called GY US Investments LLC. Marketing to wealthy Chinese nationals, the company used Trump's Mar-a-Lago resort and fundraising events as staging grounds for introductions and photo opportunities. In March 2019, concerns surfaced that Yang may have illegally funneled foreign money to the Trump Victory re-election committee.

Name: Jho Low
InternalNotes: @Lynn Walsh  Here's another new conflict. I also set this conflict status to "unclear," since it's only an investigation at this time. LMK if you think it should be otherwis?
Draft Description: Jho Low is a Malaysian businessman and fugitive from the United States. He’s thought to be living in China after swindling about $4.5 billion from the Malaysian government through a sovereign wealth fund called 1Malaysia Development Bhd, or 1MDB. The Justice Department reportedly is investigating whether Low illegally funneled $100,000 to Trump Victory, Pres. Trump’s re-election campaign operated in concert with the Republican National Committee, through American investor Larry Davis. Low allegedly gave Davis $1.5 million shortly before Davis made a donation to Trump Victory. It is illegal for political action committees to accept money from foreign nationals, even indirectly. Low has hired several political operatives close to Pres. Trump to represent him in the investigation.

Patten also admittedly funneled $50,000 from a Ukrainian official to Pres. Trump’s inauguration committee. It is illegal for political groups in the U.S. to accept money from foreign nationals.

Name: T-Mobile
InternalNotes: '@Lynn Walsh  Here's another draft description. I was a little torn by whether this merits its own conflict, because it's not like we can put every OPO customer in the database. But it really is a crystal clear example of the concern, so I went for it. (Also, we already had an earlier news peg in the database, so I tagged that, too.)
Draft Description: T-Mobile CEO John Legere has come under criticism for his company’s frequent patronage of the Old Post Office Hotel when he and other executives are in Washington, D.C. As of March 2019, T-Mobile had spent $195,000 at the hotel in the past 11 months, or about 14 percent of its cost for lodging in the capital. T-Mobile and Sprint are seeking government approval from the Justice Department and Federal Communications Commission for their proposed merger. Democratic lawmakers have scolded Legere for creating an optic of trying to curry favor with the president by patronizing his hotel, but Legere says he’s a longtime customer at Trump hotels.

6/4/2019 HN: I updated the description to reflect the consolidation, and also with the recent news about allegations of tax evasion. @Lynn Walsh Also, I added Ivanka, Jr. & Eric to this friendly-name conflict b/c they are implicated either by name in one or more article (Jr. + Eric), or by association (Ivanka) due to prior position held with the company. 

5/18/2019 HN: I went ahead and consolidated all of the Panama-related friendly names into this one.
Draft Description: "Trump Panama" in this database refers to Donald Trump's known business entities in Panama — collectively known as Trump Ocean Club, or Trump International Hotel and Tower. In 2018, Pres. Trump asked Panamanian President Juan Carlos Verala to intervene on his behalf in the wake of a high-profile scandal that devolved into a physical standoff when Trump business representatives refused to cede control of the property to investors attempting to fire them from their management role. Verala refused, and the scuffle ended with help from armed Panamanian authorities and a judicial ruling that ultimately ousted the Trump team from the property. (Under new management, the development was later renamed JW Marriott Panama.) But the conflict continues: In a 2018 lawsuit brought by the property's majority owner, the president's businesses stand accused of tax evasion, misrepresentation, financial mismanagement or misconduct, and improper destruction of records. A prior lawsuit was settled in 2016 for $75 million.
